"meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705193,"age":1,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert DeBeaufitz was born before 1336, in Devon, England, his father, Robert De Beaufitz II, was 36 and his mother, Lady Beaufitz, was 35. He married Joan Tevidall in 1376, in Gillingham, Kent, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1380, in Gillingham, Kent, England, United Kingdom, and was buried in Gillingham, Kent, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1336–1380":"enne1336–1380","1345–1380":"1345–1380","–1395":"–1395","1375–1427":"1375–1427","1300–1391":"1300–1391","1300–Female":"1300–Surnud","1337":"1337","1336":"enne 1336","1345":"1345","1300":"1300","1376":"1376","1453":"1453","1375":"1375","1395":"1395","1 January 1375":"1. jaanuar 1375","1380":"1380","1391":"1391","1427":"1427","Gillingham, Kent, England":"Gillingham, Kent, Inglismaa, United Kingdom",",Gill